General Description of Role
The Psychosocial Support Officer (Psychologist) will be responsible for the PSS care activities provided in PHCs and Women and Girls Safe Spaces inside Syria, in addition to providing continuous specialized training to ensure the preeminent care with standard practice. The position is based in Amman, Jordan.
 Main Responsibilities
 

Responsible for Psychological assessment of beneficiaries accessing PSS care in PHCs and Women and Girls Safe Spaces in Southern Syria;
Conduct remote-based PSS counselling sessions based on the individual needs and abilities of beneficiaries, through individual and group sessions;
Keep beneficiaries patients’ files updated
Update data collection of PSS activities on monthly basis, in coordination with the Protection and M&E team;
Providing continuous technical support and capacity building to the PSS staff in the field;
Providing technical support to the logistics department, ensuring technical validation of psychosocial related devices, items and equipment, as needed;
Writing technical situation reports providing relevant data, analysis and recommendations related to PSS activities;
Line managing field counterparts in South Syria (PSS Officer and PSS Assistant);
Ensure referral and integration of services provided after the counselling sessions;
Develop and facilitate trainings for Protection and Health Staff (RI staff and Program staff) on PSS;
Support the Development of IEC materials in coordination with Protection Officer and Protection Technical Coordinator
Provide guidance to Field Protection Manager and PSS Officers and protection Staff;
Coordination with Protection Officer in Jordan for joint activities between PSS and Health;

 
Required Qualifications
 

Master of Clinical Psychology or equivalent Master degree, and registration with the Jordanian Council (desired);
Degree in Psychology, Psychosocial or Social Worker (required);
At least 1 year of experience in PSS counselling and/or clinical psychology;
Experience in similar role with Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs) and/or UN agencies is preferred
Excellent verbal and written communication skills in Arabic;
Good verbal and written communication skills in English;
Demonstrable experience and/or understanding of the protection sector is necessary;
Previous experience in patient rehabilitation is a plus;
Comfortable working in remote-management settings;
Previous experience in the field of vulnerability/disability in an emergency situation with INGOs is an asset;
Adaptable and capable of working well under pressure;
Ability to work in a team setting, as well as independently without supervision;
A strong propensity for flexibility, teamwork, and creative thinking will be essential to this job.

General Description of Role
 
The Protection Officer is responsible for the continuing development and daily supervision of RI’s protection activities and services, as well as the implementation of a PSS program in South Syria. (S)he will assist in the implementation of program activities, supervise the Field Protection Managers in liaising with local community groups and INGOs to ensure the effective provision of protection services, and maintain the safety and integrity of project operations particularly as they relate to beneficiaries. The Protection Officer reports to the Cross Border Program Manager and the Protection Technical Coordinator. The position is based in Amman, Jordan.
 
 Main Responsibilities
 

Responsible for the implementation of protection activities in South Syria, including capacity building, PSS, and GBV prevention and response programs;
Develop Information, Education and Communication (IEC) materials  and community mobilization tools to promote participation and engagement of women and girls, boys and men;
Develop and facilitate capacity building activities on protection (especially GBV and PSS) for RI protection and non-protection staff and/or external partners. Train protection volunteers and community health workers to increase women and girls access to information about GBV risks and response services;
Organize and supervise participatory assessments to identify critical protection needs of IDPs and host communities, especially individuals in vulnerable situations, in order to develop effective protection interventions;

 

Provide daily supervision, support and guidance to protection staff in Syria on GBV, Psychosocial Support (PSS) and other protection concerns;
Under the supervision of the Protection Coordinator, refer GBV survivors to other specialists or other institutions for further assistance, when necessary in order to propose the best support available, maintaining confidentiality;
Develop and assist implementing new activities in Women and Girls Community Centres;
Supervise and report data collection and statistics of daily activities in Community Centres and participate in team meetings to share experiences and discuss special cases with the Field Protection Manager, always preserving confidentiality;
Coordination with Health and PSS staff to implement joint activities and activities between Health and Protection (GBV and PSS);
Engage with M&E team to develop and implement appropriate M&E plans for protection activities;
Support the regular collection and analysis of complete and up-to-date gender and protection information needed for effective program/project design and monitoring;
Ensure that all activities are implemented and coordinated based on a “do no harm” approach;
Mainstream protection and gender across all areas of intervention;
Perform other duties as required. 

 
Required Qualifications
 

Law, social work, human rights, sociology, psychology or other similar degree/diploma;    
2 years’ relevant experience with NGOs and/or UN agencies;
Excellent verbal and written communication skills in Arabic;
Good verbal and written communication skills in English;
Will have excellent self-motivation skills;
Ability to exercise sound judgment and make decisions independently;
Comfortable working in resource-deprived environment;
Good stamina to stand and work for long hours;
Adaptable and capable of working well under pressure;
Ability to work in a team setting, as well as independently without supervision;
A strong propensity for flexibility, teamwork, and creative thinking will be essential to this job.

PROGRAM/DEPARTMENT SUMMARY:
Syrian refugees and asylum seekers began fleeing the insecurity and entering the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan as early as March 2011. Currently, the estimates show that there are more than 800,000 registered and unregistered Syrian refugees residing in Jordan. Approximately 80% of Syrians refugees are living among host communities, rather than in camps. While host communities are trying to meet the needs of Syrians, they are struggling as their scarce resources continue to be stretched to the limit. Frictions between Syrians and Jordanian have emerged.
Mercy Corps has initiated conflict mitigation interventions to address growing tensions in the host communities. Mercy Corps will build capacity of Syrian and Jordanian community leaders in high-risk communities to resolve local conflicts and build consensus around common problems and joint actions required to solve them. Through small grants Syrians and Jordanians will work on joint community projects that address these sources of instability in their communities.
GENERAL POSITION SUMMARY:
The Driver will support all programs in MC Jordan mission, and occasionally also the Regional Office.The driver will provide safe, transport services for MC program and support staff within the limits of  Jordan borders. The driver will adhere to all traffic and MC safety rules and follow the transport guidelines required by the MC transport department. As program support he/she will provide logistics support organizing program stocks, MC Amman office and project sites warehouses and other logistics tasks as assigned.
ESSENTIAL JOB FUNCTIONS:
Driver and vehicles maintenance support

Operate MC vehicles as assigned by supervisor;
Maintain vehicle log-sheets in accordance with MC policies/regulations;
Check the vehicle conditions after each trip/routinely – report needs and problems to transport management;
Adhere to all safety and communication protocols as advised by Mercy Corps and supervisor;
Responsible for the safekeeping of all vehicle equipment, tools, first aid kits, spares etc.;
Keep the vehicle ready, clean and on standby – ready for  use at all times;
Assist, as required, with logistics in the office daily workloads;
Cooperate and be of assistance to staff and visitors – assist in troubleshooting potential problems during daily business;
Report all maintenance needs of the vehicle to transport management (Logistics officer and assistants) on a regular basis;
Undertake field assignments as assigned;
Work night shifts at Amman or field locations – as assigned by Supervisor -This might require occasional  airport trips at late hours of the night. Overtime and airport trips will be paid as per MC national staff handbook regulations.
Adherence to all MC policies and procedures as outlined in MC policies and procedure manuals;
Conduct himself/herself both professionally and personally in such a manner as to bring credit to Mercy Corps and to not jeopardize its humanitarian mission in country of operation;
Other duties as assigned.

Warehousing and logistics support

Follow the Mercy Corps Warehouse Policy and Procedures Guidelines
Daily coordination of MC logistical, warehouse procurement activities;
Ensure the timely delivery of supplies to respective Projects with the coordination of procurement department and MC transport pool.
Has a full understanding of MC warehouse policies and formats.
All other activities to ensure the smooth warehouse and office program stocks records are in order.

SUPERVISORY RESPONSIBILITY: None
REPORTS DIRECTLY TO: Logistics Coordinator
WORKS DIRECTLY WITH: Logistics Assistants-Drivers ,  procurement and admin teams. Coordinates with Mercy Corps program and operations staff.
KNOWLEDGE AND EXPERIENCE:
Requirements:

Valid driver’s license and at least five year driving experience.
Good English level is required, enough to communicate professionally with expats oral and writing.
Good knowledge as user level of email communications, Microsoft Word and Excel.  

Desired skills and experience: (plus)

Previous Experience with INGOs is not required, but is a plus.
Knowledge of vehicle mechanics is a plus
Knowledge of INGO common logistics procedures is a plus (not required)
Experience in warehousing and stock management procedures is a plus (not required)

About Mercy Corps
Mercy Corps is a leading global organization powered by the belief that a better world is possible. In disaster, in hardship, in more than 40 countries around the world, we partner to put bold solutions into action — helping people triumph over adversity and build stronger communities from within. Now, and for the future.
Program / Department Summary
Mercy Corps is an international relief and development organization, working in over 40 countries to build secure, productive, and just communities. Mercy Corps has worked Jordan since 2002 to implement a variety of programs funded by public institutions in the US and Europe, as well as private donors.  Mercy Corps current portfolio in Jordan focuses on economic, community, and individual relief and development. 
Within these broad objectives, Mercy Corps implements a range of projects and activities that are specifically directed at emergency, and other modes of targeted assistance for refugees and especially vulnerable populations.  Mercy Corps always pursues the highest standards of program quality and integrity, and remains dedicated to the expansion of its programming wherever there are communities or individuals in need
General Position Summary
The Director for Emergency Response and Protection will be responsible for the overall leadership, strategic direction, technical and operational management of emergency relief and vulnerable populations programming.  The director will also be responsible for identifying, engaging with, and drafting proposals for new sources of funding.  S/he will be accountable for the formulation, design, planning, implementation, coordination, compliance, and monitoring and evaluation of mercy Corps emergency response and vulnerable populations programs in Jordan.  S/he will also provide leadership and direction to ensure that emergency assistance and vulnerable population issues and approaches are integrated across the entire portfolio of Mercy Corps programming in Jordan.  S/he will ensure the quality of rigorous data collection and analysis that will tell the story of the portfolio’s activities, learning, and outcomes. S/he will directly supervise Project Managers or Coordinators, as well as other key staff supporting the portfolio.  The director will play a key role in establishing and maintaining strong relationships with relevant donors, government actors, and other relevant stakeholders.
Essential Job Responsibilities
Strategic Direction, Portfolio Quality, and Growth

Provide overall strategic direction and vision, leadership, technical and operational management of the emergency assistance and vulnerable populations portfolio;
Lead the development of MC Jordan’s strategy for emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming;
Maintain MC Jordan’s readiness to respond to sudden crises – natural or man-made – in which emergency assistance is required and/or vulnerable populations are threatened;
Lead integrated sector design processes in order to bridge all programmatic elements of the emergency assistance and vulnerable populations portfolio;
Carry out effective oversight of emergency assistance and vulnerable populations projects and assessments.

Team Management

Supervise project managers and similar staff to implement high-quality programming;
Ensure that teams fully adhere to international standards in technical and organizational implementation, including the inclusion of gender, conflict-management, and participatory approaches to ensure that Do No Harm and other fundamental principles are fully respected;
Supervise and mentor project staff to effectively manage projects, including workplan creation, budget forecasting and monitoring, accurate and timely reporting, and efficient use of resources; communicated clear expectations, set performance objectives, provide regular and timely performance feedback, conduct annual performance reviews;
Ensure that promotion, increase, and task-assignment policies and procedures are fully compliant with country-office standards;
Build technical capacity of national staff on emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming;
Ensure staff compliance with financial and operational policies, procedures, and systems.

Technical Leadership

Build a culture of collaboration and find opportunities for programmatic integration of emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming. Also work with other senior country office leadership to link these programs in the sector to other programs in the country portfolio;
Strengthen existing management and information systems - to document achievement of measurable milestones for emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming, and to ensure timely compliance with donor requirements;
Oversee and support efforts to collect data, conduct assessments and research on emergency assistance and vulnerable populations opportunities in Jordan for use in strategic program development and advocacy;
Provide technical leadership and guidance to the INGO Forum’s Protection Working Group.

Representation and Coordination

Represent Mercy Corps at the INGO Forum’s Protection working group and participate in other relevant coordination mechanisms as-needed;
Cultivate strategic partnerships and maintain effective working relationships with key government, IPO/INGO, civil-society and private-sector stakeholders to advance organizational sector strategies related to emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming;
Liaise with key stakeholders to coordinate responses and identify strategies to facilitate market-based interventions with programmatic synergies;
Liaise with regional and global technical support unites to identify strategies for strengthening programs and to promote Mercy Corps’ though leadership on emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming in Jordan and across the region;
Represent Mercy Corps in strategic meetings on emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming;
Ensure the application of Mercy Corps’ Code of Conduct, Child Safeguarding Protocols, Prevention of Sexual Exploitation and Abuse Policy, Gender Policy and Community Accountability Response Mechanism (CARM) guidelines.

Organizational Learning  

As part of our commitment to organizational learning and in support of our understanding that learning organizations are more effective, efficient and relevant to the communities they serve, we expect all team members to commit 5% of their time to learning activities that benefit Mercy Corps as well as themselves.

Accountability to Beneficiaries 

Mercy Corps team members are expected to support all efforts toward accountability, specifically
	to our beneficiaries and to international standards guiding international relief and development work, while actively engaging beneficiary communities as equal partners in the design, monitoring and evaluation of our field projects.


Supervisory Responsibility: Project Managers
Accountability
Reports Directly To: Director of Programs
Works Directly With: Program, Operations, Finance, IDL, Human Resources, regional Technical Support Unit, and HQ support teams
Knowledge and Experience

BA/S or equivalent in management, sociology, political science, international development, international relations, or related field;
10-12 years of progressive experience and proven record of achievements in designing and implementing programs related to emergency assistance and vulnerable populations;
Strong strategic thinker with demonstrable capacity to translate concepts into action;
Demonstrated experience leading diverse teams toward a common vision;
Experience in emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming required; specialized background in child protection, women’s programming, youth programming, livelihoods, education, programming for the disabled highly desired;
Prior work experience in Jordan highly desired;
Prior experience working with UNICEF highly preferred;
Strong organizational management skills, including previous experience managing international teams to successfully plan and implement quality programming;
Ability to build strong systems that enable timely and quality program delivery;
Demonstrated ability to implement programs with rigorous deliverables and timelines in accordance with timeframes and donor regulations;
Demonstrated ability to respond to multiple priorities in a timely manner, producing high-quality outcomes;
Proven track record in staff and stakeholder training, mentoring, and capacity building;
Ability and interest working with a multi-ethnic team in a culturally appropriate manner;
Proficiency in English essential and Arabic highly desired.

Success Factors
The Director for emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming will have extensive experience in leading teams, in both administrative and technical capacities, with a proven track record of strategic planning, programmatic achievement, management skill, diplomacy and team-building.  S/he will be a decisive leader, exercise sound judgment, possess excellent communication, interpersonal and analytical skills and have a high level of integrity and flexibility to adapt to conditions of ongoing change.  S/he is able to prioritize among competing tasks while also filling in gaps as needed to ensure the success of the overall emergency assistance and vulnerable populations programming portfolio.  The Director for emergency assistance and vulnerable populations is a strategic and solutions-driven thinker with the ability to articulate and translate innovative ideas into solid programming and to build positive relationships with his or her team, and with key stakeholders at various levels.
Living Conditions / Environmental Conditions
The position is based in Amman, Jordan.  The location is accompanied and is not eligible for hardship or R&R.  Staff will have access to good medical services and the living situation is of a high standard.  Water and electricity are present with occasional cuts.  This position requires travel to field sites within Jordan.
Mercy Corps team members represent the agency both during and outside work hours when deployed in a field posting or on a visit/TDY to a field posting. Team members are expected to conduct themselves in a professional manner and respect local laws, customs and MC's policies, procedures, and values at all times and in all in-country venues

Logistics Assistant & Driver – NRC Syria Response Office
Do you have minimum of 3 years experience working as Logistics Assistant & Driver ? Are you interested in working with an international organization?
If you are looking for new challenges and interested in working with one of the world's most effective and respected Humanitarian Organizations then you would be interested in our announced position for an  Logistics Assistant & Driver – Syria Response Office, Amman.
Our Ideal Candidate is a team worker, an analytical person, and someone who is able to communicate effectively with impact and respect. Confidentiality and trustworthy are core requirements for this position.

Holder of a valid Jordanian driving license and knowledge in the Jordanian driving regulations is a must.
The purpose of the Logistics Assistant and Driver is to support the effective operation of the NRC Syria Response Office (SRO) and related programme activities, by providing general logistic assistance and driving duties in accordance with NRC’s administrative, finance and logistics policies and procedures and relevant donor guidelines.
 Job tasks and responsibilities: 
• Transport NRC staff, visitors, documents and goods/materials to designated destinations when officially approved;
• Adhere to the NRC Driver’s Manual and respect the local traffic regulations at all times;
• Ensure the safety and security of the passengers, the goods, and the vehicle at all times;
• Maintain the vehicles in the proper operating condition at all times, including keeping the vehicles clean, performing daily/weekly vehicle checks, and following up on regular servicing and maintenance;
• Management of the SRO car pool, including vehicle allocation and the preparation of monthly fleet report;
• Adhere to NRC’s administrative, finance and logistics policies, procedures and audit standards;
• Provide general administrative and logistics assistance at the SRO
• Provide assistance with local procurement, in accordance with NRC procurement procedures and thresholds, where required and as delegated by line management;
Ability  to work in basic to intermediate English (written and spoken) is a must. 
Basic computer skills in Microsoft Office (MS Excel, Word, and Outlook)
 
Note: NRC may be required to verify the identity of its partners and to check that its partners have not been involved in illegal activities. NRC reserves the right to use electronic screening tools for this purpose.
