The mission of Global Communities (formerly CHF International) is to create long-lasting, positive and community-led change that improves the lives and livelihoods of vulnerable people across the globe. Global Communities seeks a IT Specialist for USA1D YouthPower/Jordan Activity, a five-year, $23 million, USAID-funded contract. This is an open position for a recently awarded program.
The IT Specialist will be responsible for providing IT support to the project office. The IT Specialist may also provide support to other project offices in Jordan. Specific responsibilities include. 
Roles and Responsibilities
• Support Windows PCs operating on Windows 7 or newer.
• Ensure Windows and other software is maintained and that patches are promptly applied on computers in the local office. • Ensure anti-virus software is kept current.
• Ensure information is backed up and maintained in accordance with Global Communities policies and procedures.
• Provide user support on hardware, networking and software related issues.
• Configure and troubleshoot laptops / desktops / printers for staff and hub centers.
• Install Network Printers;
• Ensure that internet is working properly in project office and sites;
• Configure email on Outlook for new staff and troubleshooting email issues in coordination with HQ IT Team;
• Provide first level of support to the maintaining network infrastructure including ISP, router, and Ethernet switch;
• Maintain relevant databases for the project; • Help ensure that project website is functioning. 
Education 
• Bachelor's degree with a minimum of three years of experience in supporting information technology systems.
• Any IT Certifications will be a plus. 
Qualifications 
• Knowledge and experience with Windows Microsoft Office systems;
• Ability to work independently and make decisions in accordance with established policies and regulations;
• Ability to troubleshoot connectivity and other issues related to staff IT issues;
• Willingness to learn and pick up new skills;
• HTML or Java Script experience and knowledge highly desired for updating website content.
• Jordanian national

Director of Finance and Administration — Jordan YouthPower 
The mission of Global Communities (formerly CHF International) is to create long-lasting, positive and community-led change that improves the lives and livelihoods of vulnerable people across the globe. Global Communities seeks a Director of Finance and Administration (DFA) for USAID Jordan YouthPower, a five year 23M USAID program. Jordan YouthPower is a USAID contract. This is an open position for a recently awarded program. 
The DFA will be responsible for the primary oversight of all financial reporting and administrative operations through the life of the program. In particular, s/he will oversee financial operations for the project and conduct continual reporting to ensure the financial health of the project and the correct usage of funds. This position reports to the Chief of Party. 
Responsibilities 
• Provide financial management for all aspects of the program; 
• Develop and maintain sound financial management systems in line with USAID rules and regulations and Global Communities' policies and procedures, and accounting principles;
• Manage the project budget ensuring all costs incurred by Global Communities are accounted for and in compliance with local laws;
• Provide financial control, prepare and analyze budgets, develop financial reports, and make recommendations to HQ on budget expenditures; 
• Maintain updated information regarding grants and contracts, reporting requirements and financial restrictions; • Provide oversight on all program related financial matters;
• Ensure financial reporting is in accordance with USAID contractual requirements; 
• Oversee Operations and Administration staff, ensuring that functions are performed timely and accurately 
Qualifications and experience 
• Bachelors or advanced degree in accounting, finance or related area; MBA in Finance or Accounting preferred • Minimum of five years managing finance, preferably on a USAID funded programs;
• Ten or more years finance department or international development experience with progressively increasing responsibility;
• Proven experience with U.S. Government-funded contracts; 
• Demonstrated understanding of USAID rules and regulations 
• Strong managerial skills and experience overseeing staff; 
• Ability to set up financial regulation systems with partner organizations to ensure the efficient and accurate disbursement of funds; 
• Fluency in written and spoken English required

PROGRAM/DEPARTMENT SUMMARY:
Mercy Corps is an international relief and development organization working in over 40 countries worldwide helping people build secure, productive and just communities. In Jordan, Mercy Corps has been actively working since 2002 to implement a variety of programs funded by US and European governments and private donors. The current portfolio includes programs focusing on improved water demand management, conflict mitigation and social cohesion programming, child, youth and inclusive education programming, and humanitarian relief programming, which includes emergency cash and protection programming. 
With funding from the Dutch government, Mercy Corps will implement a three-year project which aims to improve access to justice, as well as increase incomes and employment opportunities for vulnerable Jordanians and Syrians in host-communities of Mafraq and Irbid governorates. The project will provide referral and protection services, facilitate access to vocational training and apprenticeships, and strengthen micro, small, and medium-sized businesses in several sectors. Sectors will be strengthened using Mercy Corps’ Market Systems development approach. The key to a successful sustainable program will be to establish partnerships and linkages with private and/or public sector providers of services. Efforts will be made to promote youth and women throughout all activities.
GENERAL POSITION SUMMARY:
Mercy Corps is looking for an energetic and experienced Project Manager (PM) with knowledge and experience in market development and workforce development in Jordan. The PM will provide operational leadership to the project consortium, consisting of one INGO partner, and anticipated private/public sector sub-awardees in Irbid and Mafraq. The PM will lead a team of 10 staff, including a coordinator, five field officers, and two M&E officers. The PM will supervise the work of several consultants for the market systems assessment, youth-led labor market assessment and baseline research activities during the inception phase. The PM is responsible for all aspects of the program, including workplanning, budget, reporting, recruiting, team leadership, MEAL, compliance, donor relationship, coordination with consortium partners, and project representation. The PM for this project will be detail oriented with excellent planning and communication skills. H/She will be an entrepreneur who understands how the private sector operates.    
Essential Duties and Responsibilities:
Project Management 

Hire and build a strong team of capable coordinators and officers;
Create a positive can-do culture within the project team, promoting creativity, communication, hard work, and much laughter;
Develop and implement work plans focused on key outputs and outcomes;
Lead the development of market assessments, community mapping, training curriculum and business support activities, beneficiary outreach, and create mechanisms to prepare partners and relevant staff to implement activities;
Lead the development of competitive grants for vocational training providers and MSMEs;
Ensure all programming follows Mercy Corps’ internal systems and procedures;
Implement best practices of adaptive management and market-based development approaches;
Lead coordinator and officers and ensure that they have the capacity to succeed; organize trainings;
Guide development of data collection and monitoring tools and oversee program team to collect data and analyze results;
Ensure all programming follows Mercy Corps’ Code of Conduct by increasing team capacity to disseminate and apply;


Identify and support mechanisms for effective project monitoring and evaluation efforts and systems for information sharing internally and externally;
Write regular donor and organizational reports to highlight program successes and challenges;
Oversee program budget and complete financial planning to inform programming;
Monitor expenditures and forecasts;
Adhere to all MC procurement, logistics and administrative regulations related to programming;
Conduct frequent supervisory visits to the field to monitor project implementation and ensure project quality;
Collaborate with local stakeholders including municipalities, Chambers of Commerce, business associations, vocational training providers, MSMEs, Ministry of Social Affairs (MOSA), and other donor-funded projects to ensure successful program implementation;

 Coordination and Representation

Liaise and coordinate directly with Consortium partners to ensure project implementation strategies, workplans, data collection tools, etc. are harmonized and in-line with agreed approaches of the Consortium
Coordinate with donor and government agencies to provide updates on programming as needed;
Coordinate with other Mercy Corps pillars, including youth, social stability, and water/energy to synchronize responses;
Participate in workshops and tasks forces, as needed, to inform strategy development and improved service delivery;
Contribute to development communication materials that highlight Mercy Corps’ programming;
Participate in planning and implementation of the Mercy Corps Jordan’s livelihoods/economic development programming, communications, advocacy, and program development;
Participate in INGO, UNHCR, and USAID Livelihoods working groups;
Support program development related to livelihoods programming, while contributing to other related to programming, as needed;
Represent Mercy Corps’ work at Amman and field-based levels, as needed, to foster greater connections and information sharing.

Other

Fulfill Mercy Corps Program Management Minimum Standards based on the organization-wide guide;
Ensure activities promote gender equity, conflict sensitivity, and environmental awareness by applying Do No Harm and Mercy Corps’ Gender Equity policy;
Participate in internal office coordination and planning meetings and workshops;
Conduct himself/herself both professionally and personally in such a manner as to bring credit to Mercy Corps and to not jeopardize its humanitarian mission;
Ensure compliance with security procedures and policies as determined by country leadership;
Proactively ensure that team members operate in a secure environment and are aware of policies.
Other assigned tasks, as necessary.

SUPERVISORY RESPONSIBILITY: Oversees a project team of 8 staff, with direct supervisory responsibility of Project Coordinator, Project Officers and M&E Officers.  
REPORTS DIRECTLY TO: Director of Economic Opportunities
WORKS DIRECTLY WITH: Programs Director, Director of Economic Growth and Responsibilities, MEL department, Finance, Admin and Procurement teams.
KNOWLEDGE AND EXPERIENCE:

B.Sc equivalent in, management, economics, international development, social science, or other relevant field; Master preferred;
5-7 years of progressive experience and proven high level of competence in working in economic and market development, workforce development, and/or development-related programs, ideally in relief and/or post-conflict settings;
Demonstrated management experience required;
Ability to successfully design, implement, and manage economic development programming;
Experience with local and/or international NGO is required;
Experience with private sector partnerships preferred;
Experience providing cost-shared business expansion grants to MSMEs preferred;
Strong experience with monitoring, evaluation, data collection and analysis preferred
Entrepreneurs with private sector experience preferred;
Experience managing European-funded program preferred;
Strong leadership and communication skills and sense of humor;
Excellent writing and communication skills required;
Ability and interest to work with a multi-ethnic team in a culturally appropriate manner; and
Fluency in written and spoken Arabic and English essential

SUCCESS FACTORS:

Deep commitment to humanitarian principles and values
Ability to work under pressure, independently and with limited supervision
Demonstrated creative problem-solving skills
Security, political and cultural aware
Highly developed interpersonal communication skills
Demonstrated decision-making and leadership skills and excellent time management capacities.
Experience in all phases of project management
Good sense of humor

Action Contre la Faim (ACF)  is an international non-governmental organization working in more than 40 countries in the fields of nutrition, food security and livelihoods, water sanitation and hygiene, and care practices. ACF is looking for its program in Jordan for community mobiliser.
Work place: AZRAQ Camp  
Main Objective : 
Support and monitor WASH committees;
Ensure WASH committee involvement in hygiene promotion activities;
Manage the monitoring of WASH block cleanliness and maintenance;
Mobilize the camp population to ACF approved WASH messages;
Ensure community participation in WASH Soft and Hard activities; and
Support distribution of materials to beneficiaries.
 
Specific Objectives:
Objective 1: To mobilize the refugee community in the camp towards hygiene promotion best practices and ensure community participation in the design and implementation of both Soft and Hard WASH activities in the camp
 

Attend camp community based activities (info sessions, community representative meetings, etc) providing update on ACF projects and collecting feedback from refugees in coordination with the M&E team;
Support the Community Liaison Officer in community mobilization activities on the plot level to ensure community participation;
Carry out data collection activities to collect suggestions and feedback on WASH solutions and services in the camp;
Carry out Post distribution activities in coordination with the M&E team;
Closely monitor hygiene practice in the camp and report on the status; and
Address complaints and discuss behaviour change practices with refugees on the plot level.

 
Objective 2: Mobilize the community during the implementing of hygiene promotion activities

Engage community representatives and community leaders in hygiene promotion activities, including activities ACF is implementing in coordination with other INGOs; and
Support other ACF teams as needed in implementing any other hygiene promotion activities that ACF leads in the camp

 
 
Objective 3: To contribute in establishing, supporting and monitoring WASH committees 
 
Activities:

Mobilize the camp community to elect their WASH committees;
Carry out WASH committees establishment activities including negotiating TORs and furnishing induction;
Contribute in developing a minimum standard for the performance of the WASH committees;
Undertake a capacity assessment of each committee and use this to develop a corresponding capacity building plan for the Operations and Maintenance work;
Provide the necessary support (training, etc.) to the WASH committees as detailed by the capacity building plan to enable them to carry out Operations and maintenance activities; and
Undertake routine monitoring of the WASH committees performance using the tools developed, and revise the capacity building plan as required.

 
Objective 4: Carry out the distribution of WASH materials to beneficiaries, and ensure community participation

Ensure community participation to make decisions on content of kits;
Mobilize the community to decide on the distribution mechanisms;
Work with the WASH committees to ensure smooth and convenient distribution of materials;
Implement distribution activities; and
Collecting feedback from community on distribution process and content.

 
Objective 5: Provide accurate and timely information to Community Liaison Officer
Activities:

Carry out monitoring tools for WASH committee assessments and monitoring;
Submit week reports for all implemented activities; and

Maintain filing and proper recording of data.
 
Previous experience needed:   

Two years of experience working in community mobilization

Education : 

University or diploma degree 

The application period closes on  30 of March 2017
Before applying, please make sure that you have read the requirements for the position and that you qualify.
Applications from non-qualifying applicants will most likely be discarded by the recruiting manager.
ACF is committed to creating a diverse environment and is proud to be an equal opportunity employer.

Action Against Hunger is an international non-governmental organization working in more than 40 countries in the fields of nutrition, food security and livelihoods, water sanitation and hygiene, mental health and care practices. In Jordan, Action Against Hunger is working in Irbid Governorate, carrying out activities in support of vulnerable Syrians and Jordanians.
 
Under the current programs, Action Against Hunger supports vulnerable families in WaSH and Livelihood activities.
 
